'''Jon Berg''' is a special-effects artist and occasional actor for the ''Star Wars'' saga. He appeared as an actor in the cantina scene for [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']] ([[1977]]).

==Biography==
Berg worked as a stop-motion animator, as Harryhausen did before him, for [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']] ([[1977]]). He moved different creatures, especially in the famous cantina scene, and he was also supposed to act as different aliens. Although uncredited, he is known to have played [[Momaw Nadon]], the [[Ithorian|"Hammerhead"]]; and also one of the arguing [[Duro]]s. He may have played one of the [[Figrin D'an and the Modal Nodes|cantina band members]], particularly [[Tech Mo'r]], the [[ommni box]] player; however, this role is unconfirmed and even today a polemic question among experts.

He returned to the ''Star Wars'' saga for [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''Star Wars'': Episode V ''The Empire Strikes Back'']] ([[1980]]), again as a stop-motion animator, although he was not officially billed for that part.

Berg returned to [[George Lucas]]' crew for [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']] ([[1983]]) as a creature consultant. The following year, [[John Korty]]'s TV movie [[Caravan of Courage: An Ewok Adventure|''The Ewok Adventure'']] ([[1984]]) featured special effects by Berg and ''Star Wars'' colleagues Dennis Muren, Phil Tippett and [[Michael Pangrazio]]. All of them got an Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects, although shared with other TV movies and series. The book ''Industrial Light & Magic: The Art of Special Effects'' (1986, Thomas G. Smith) says that Berg also portrayed the [[Gorax]] in the movie.

His experience with Burton would be useful more than ten years after that, when he joined the ''Star Wars'' saga for a fifth time, working as model maker in the sixth installment of the saga, [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']] ([[2005]]). In the meantime, Jon Berg has also been responsible for creating the statue used for the [[Fan Film Awards]], and he was also credited as guest animator in the short ''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars Episode II]]''.

